1 Introduction
1.1 Motivation and Background
Cancer kills approximately 10 million people annually worldwide, making it the second
leading cause of death globally [Sung et al., 2021]. Despite enormous investment in
research and treatment, the fundamental dynamics of how a tumour grows, evades
the immune system, and invades surrounding tissue remain incompletely understood.
Classical models — from the Gompertz growth equation to reaction-diffusion PDE
models — treat the tumour as a spatially smooth, mechanistically deterministic object.
These models can reproduce average growth curves, but they systematically fail to
explain the heterogeneity of tumour growth: the sudden explosive phases of invasion,
the long quiescent periods, and the catastrophic metastatic transitions that define the
natural history of aggressive cancers.
Complexity science offers a radically different lens. A tissue is not a homogeneous
medium — it is a network of ∼ 1010 interacting cells connected by physical contacts,
gap junctions, paracrine signalling cascades, and extracellular matrix scaffolding. When
we adopt this network perspective, the hallmarks of cancer described by Hanahan &
Weinberg [2011] — sustained proliferation, invasion, angiogenesis, immune evasion —
can be reinterpreted as network-theoretic phenomena: hub nodes (stem cells, super
spreader cells) driving preferential recruitment, percolation transitions marking the
onset of invasion, and avalanche dynamics governing the episodic burst-and-quiescence
pattern of growth.
The concept of Self-Organised Criticality (SOC), introduced by Bak et al. [1987],
provides the unifying mathematical framework. An SOC system is one that sponta
neously evolves toward a critical state — a state poised at the boundary between order
and disorder — without requiring external tuning of any control parameter. At this
critical point, perturbations trigger responses (avalanches) of all possible sizes, de
scribed by power-law statistics with no characteristic scale. The paradigmatic example
is the sandpile: grains added one at a time cause avalanches ranging from single-grain
relaxations to system-spanning collapses.
Is a tumour an SOC system? We argue yes, for the following reasons:
• Mutations accumulate slowly (the “slow drive”), while malignant conversion and
recruitment propagate rapidly through signalling networks (the “fast relaxation”).
• Empirical studies of tumour heterogeneity reveal scale-free clone-size distributions
[Sottoriva et al., 2015], consistent with SOC.
• Metastasis — the catastrophic spread of cancer to distant sites — has the hallmarks
of a percolation transition: a sudden, system-spanning cascade that cannot be
