1.2 Objectives of this Project
This project addresses four research questions:
1. Is a tissue/tumour network a good candidate for complexity-science analysis, and
specifically for the SOC framework?
2. Canaminimalnetwork-based agent model reproduce the known statistical signatures
of tumour growth (power laws, long-range correlations)?
3. How does intercellular connectivity k shape the “avalanche” dynamics of malignant
recruitment?
4. Does the simulated system exhibit spontaneous self-organisation toward a critical
state?
1.3 Scope and Novelty
While several authors have applied complex-network ideas to cancer biology [Barab´asi
et al., 2011, Hanahan & Weinberg, 2011], a unified treatment of tumour invasion as
a SOC phenomenon on a Barab´asi–Albert tissue network, with explicit avalanche
statistics and percolation analysis, constitutes a novel contribution at the intersection
of computational oncology and complexity science.
2 The Tumour as a Complex System
2.1 Why Cancer is a Good Candidate for SOC Analysis
A system is a good candidate for SOC if it satisfies the following structural criteria
[Bak, 1996, Jensen, 1998]:
2.1.1 Many interacting agents with local rules
A tissue contains billions of cells whose behaviour is governed by local biochemical
signals: growth factors, contact inhibition, gap-junction coupling, cytokine gradients.
No single cell has global information about the tissue state. This is the defining
characteristic of an agent-based complex system.
2.1.2 Separation of timescales: slow drive, fast relaxation
Oncogenic mutations accumulate over years to decades (the slow drive), while a
recruitment cascade — once a threshold is crossed — can propagate through a lo
