cal neighbourhood within hours via paracrine signalling (the fast relaxation). This
separation is the essential prerequisite for SOC dynamics [Bak et al., 1987].
2.1.3 Threshold-triggered cascades
When a cell’s accumulated mutation load exceeds the Vogelstein multi-hit threshold
[Vogelstein et al., 2013], it undergoes malignant transformation and begins secreting
growth factors that lower the transformation threshold of neighbouring cells. This is
mathematically identical to the toppling rule in a sandpile or the threshold cascade in
a financial network.
2.1.4 Absence of characteristic scale
Empirical measurements of clone-size distributions in human colon cancer [Sottoriva et
al., 2015] and breast cancer [Yates et al., 2015] exhibit power-law behaviour spanning
many orders of magnitude — a definitive signature that the system has no characteristic
scale and is operating near criticality.
2.1.5 Scale-free network topology
Protein–protein interaction networks, gene regulatory networks, and intercellular sig
nalling networks all exhibit scale-free degree distributions P(k) ∼ k−γ with γ ≈ 2–3
[Barab´asi & Albert, 1999], arising from preferential attachment (new signalling connec
tions preferentially form to already well-connected hub nodes, e.g. oncoproteins such
as TP53, MYC, EGFR).
