2.2.2 Avalanche
An avalanche (malignant recruitment cascade) is triggered when a cell’s mutation
load mi ≥ θ = 5 (the multi-hit threshold). The cell converts to cancerous and begins
recruiting its healthy neighbours: each healthy neighbour j converts with probability
ρ =0.25 per contact per step, propagating the cascade wave-front. The avalanche size
s is the total number of cells that convert during a single cascade event. Biologically,
this represents the episodic explosive growth observed in histopathological studies.
Open boundary conditions (cells with no neighbours lose recruitment pressure) provide
the dissipation channel that prevents unlimited cascade growth and sustains the critical
state.
