3 Model Description and Simulation
3.1 Tissue Network Construction
The tissue is represented as a Barab´asi–Albert (BA) preferential-attachment network
with N =300 nodes and m = 2 edges added per new node. The BA model is chosen
because:
• It generates a scale-free degree distribution P(k) ∝ k−3, matching empirical inter
cellular signalling networks.
• Hub nodes (high-degree cells) naturally model oncogenic driver nodes (e.g. cells
overexpressing EGFR, HER2, or TP53 mutant protein) that have disproportionate
influence on their neighbourhood.
• New edges form preferentially to well-connected nodes, mimicking angiogenesis and
paracrine signalling recruitment.
The resulting network has mean degree ¯ k ≈ 3.56 and maximum degree kmax ≈ 22.
