4 Results and Analysis
4.1 Tumour Growth Dynamics
Figure 1(a) shows the tumour cell count over the simulation. After a brief latent period
during which mutations accumulate in the seed cells, the tumour undergoes rapid,
autocatalytic growth driven by recruitment cascades. The growth is not smooth — it
is composed of discrete episodic jumps, each corresponding to an avalanche event. By
t ≈ 248, all 300 cells have been invaded. This qualitatively reproduces the clinically
observed pattern of slow occult growth followed by explosive invasion.
The mutation-load distribution at the end of the simulation (Figure 1(b)) shows that
all cells have reached the threshold θ = 5, confirming full malignant conversion. Cells
that converted earliest carry the highest loads, reflecting the stochastic heterogeneity
in mutation timing — a feature consistent with the “Big Bang” model of tumour
evolution [Sottoriva et al., 2015].
