The exponent α ≈ 1.0 is consistent with theoretical predictions for SOC cascades on
scale-free networks [Goh et al., 2003], where network hubs amplify cascade propagation
and flatten the size distribution compared to regular lattices (where α ≈ 1.5). The
R2 = 0.72 reflects the finite-size scatter inherent to a 300-node network; the linear
log–log relationship spans nearly two orders of magnitude.
The complementary cumulative distribution function (CCDF) in Figure 2(a) confirms
the power-law heavy tail: the probability that a cascade exceeds size s decays as a
power law, with large avalanches (size ≥ 50) occurring with probability ∼ 5%, far
exceeding any Gaussian or Poisson prediction. In clinical terms, this means that
roughly 1-in-20 “trigger events” (new mutation, immune suppression episode) leads to
a massive, potentially lethal invasion cascade.
4.3 Tumour Sub-Network Connectivity
Figure 1(e) shows the evolution of tumour sub-network connectivity k(t). Once tumour
growth initiates, connectivity rises rapidly and stabilises at a mean value of ¯ k ≈ 3.56.
This self-tuning of connectivity — without any external parameter adjustment — is
the hallmark of SOC: the system spontaneously organises its internal state to maintain
the criticality conditions for ongoing cascades.
The stabilisation at ¯ k ≈ 3.56 is not arbitrary. From the percolation analysis (Sec
tion 4.5), the critical connectivity for system-spanning cascades is kc ≈ 4. The tumour
sub-network thus sits just below the percolation threshold — a state of marginal
criticality that maximises sensitivity to perturbations while maintaining finite-size
cascades. This is the SOC attractor.
4.4 Degree Distribution of the Tumour Sub-Network
Figure 2(b) shows the degree distribution of the tumour sub-network at the end of the
simulation. The distribution exhibits a power-law tail, confirming that the tumour
sub-network inherits the scale-free topology of the underlying BA tissue network.
This has a profound implication: the tumour contains hub cells — high-degree nodes
with disproportionately many signalling connections — that act as super-spreaders of
