4.5 Percolation Phase Transition
Figure 1(f) shows the cascade fraction as a function of mean degree k in the Erd˝os–R´enyi
percolation model. The results reveal a sharp phase transition:
• For k ≲ 3: cascades remain localised (fraction < 0.15). Tumours in tissues with
sparse intercellular connectivity are contained.
• For k ≈ 4: a percolation transition occurs. Cascades begin to span a significant
fraction of the network.
• For k ≳5: cascades are system-spanning (fraction > 0.70). Full tumour invasion is
inevitable once initiated.
This phase transition identifies kc ≈ 4 as the critical connectivity — the network
theoretic invasion threshold. Therapies that reduce intercellular connectivity below kc
(e.g. tight-junction enhancers, cadherin modulators, anti-angiogenic drugs) would push
the system into the subcritical regime, preventing system-spanning cascades even if
individual malignant conversions still occur.
4.6 Long-Range Correlations: Hurst Exponent
Figure 2(c) shows the rolling Hurst exponent of the tumour-growth time series,
computed over a sliding window of 40 steps. The Hurst exponent is consistently
H ≈0.98 ≫0.5, indicating extreme persistence: growth increments at one time are
strongly positively correlated with increments at all future times. This is the temporal
f
ingerprint of criticality — in a subcritical system, H → 0.5 (random diffusion), while
at the critical point H → 1 (persistent, scale-free dynamics).
The high H is biologically meaningful: once a tumour begins growing, its trajectory is
highly predictable in direction (upward) but unpredictable in magnitude (the episodic
jumps have power-law sizes). This matches the clinical observation that progressive
disease is common but the rate of progression is highly variable.
