5 Discussion
5.1 Evidence for a Self-Organised Critical State
The simulation provides compelling evidence that the modelled tumour network operates
as a self-organised critical system. Three independent lines of evidence converge:
1. Scale-free avalanche distribution. The power-law exponent α ≈ 1.0 is robust
across the full range of simulated cascade sizes (1 to 113 cells), with no exponential
cutoff that would indicate subcritical dynamics. In a subcritical system, the distribution
would be exponential; in a supercritical system, it would be dominated by a single giant
cascade. The power-law spanning two orders of magnitude is the unique signature of
criticality.
2. Spontaneous connectivity self-tuning. The tumour sub-network connectivity
k(t) converges to ¯ k ≈ 3.56 without any external control. This value is not arbitrary —
it sits just below the percolation threshold kc ≈ 4, maintaining the system in a state of
marginal criticality: large cascades are possible but not inevitable at every step. This
self-tuning is the defining property of SOC and cannot arise from a non-critical system.
3. Long-range temporal correlations. The Hurst exponent H ≈ 0.98 implies that
growth increments are correlated across all accessible timescales. This rules out a
Markovian (memoryless) growth process and is consistent with the long-range avalanche
propagation expected at a critical point.
5.2 Biological Implications
Hub cells as therapeutic targets. The scale-free topology of the tumour sub
network implies the existence of high-degree hub cells — likely corresponding to cancer
