stem cells or oncogene-overexpressing driver cells. The theory of scale-free network
robustness [Barab´asi et al., 2000] predicts that random killing of cells (chemotherapy)
is relatively ineffective against scale-free networks (which are robust to random node
removal), while targeted killing of hubs (e.g. EGFR-targeted therapy, HER2-targeted
therapy) is catastrophically effective. This is precisely the rationale behind modern
targeted oncology.
Connectivity as the systemic risk lever. The percolation analysis identifies
connectivity k as the key control parameter for invasion risk. Therapies that reduce
connectivity — by inhibiting gap junctions, disrupting paracrine signalling loops, or
blocking angiogenic network formation — can push the system from the supercritical to
the subcritical regime, preventing system-spanning invasion even if individual malignant
conversions cannot be eliminated. This aligns with the rationale for anti-angiogenic
therapies such as bevacizumab.
The “no warning” problem. Because all cascades — small and large — belong to
the same power-law ensemble, there is no simple local observable that predicts which
small conversion event will grow into a massive invasion cascade. This has a sobering
implication for early cancer detection: local genomic markers (mutation count in a
biopsy sample) do not predict systemic invasion risk. What matters is the network-level
connectivity — a quantity that can only be inferred from whole-tissue imaging or
multi-site biopsy studies.
5.3 Effect of Necrosis Rate
In the primary simulation, necrosis was set to zero to study pure invasion dynamics.
With a finite necrosis rate ν > 0, the dynamics shift:
• For small ν (≲ 0.01): the tumour still invades but more slowly, with a larger fraction
of cells cycling through Cancerous → Necrotic → (vacant) → ..., producing a
necrotic core — a classical histopathological feature.
• For large ν (≳ 0.05): the necrosis rate exceeds the recruitment rate and the
tumour is contained — corresponding to a functioning immune response or effective
chemotherapy.
This competition between recruitment and necrosis defines a phase boundary in the
(ρ, ν) parameter space that could be mapped in future work.
