to ¯ k ≈ 3.56, just below the percolation threshold kc ≈ 4, without any external
parameter adjustment. This is the defining signature of SOC.
3. Percolation phase transition: A sharp transition in cascade fraction at kc ≈
4 identifies connectivity as the key systemic risk parameter. Anti-connective
therapies offer a principled network- theoretic strategy for preventing system
spanning invasion.
4. Persistent long-range correlations: The Hurst exponent H ≈ 0.98 confirms that
tumour growth is a persistent, non- Markovian process with correlations spanning
all accessible timescales, consistent with criticality.
The central conclusion is that tumour invasion is not a smooth, deterministic growth
process — it is an intermittent, scale-free avalanche phenomenon driven by a complex
network operating near a critical point. This perspective reframes cancer not as a
disease of individual cells but as a disease of the network — and points toward a new
class of network-targeted therapies based on connectivity reduction rather than bulk
cytotoxicity.
